1 Reading data into R

When working with your own data, you need some way to get it into R. This is known as reading in your data. Data will come in many different formats, and there are many different ways to read it in. In this lab we will focus on reading in files. CSV files are a very common form of data storage and are text files comprised of rows (observations), with fields separated by commas. They look something like this when you open them in a text editor:

Figure 1.1: Image credit: Lifewire.com

To read in data, we are going to use the package readr, which is part of the tidyverse. The tidyverse is “an opinionated collection of R packages designed for data science. All packages share an underlying design philosophy, grammar, and data structures.” According to the R Data Science team, using the tidyverse “makes data science faster, easier and more fun” and I happen to agree. We will use the tidyverse a lot in this course.

To install a package, run:

install.packages("tidyverse")

If you get a message in your console (where the code runs at the bottom of RStudio) that says:

Do you want to install from sources the package which needs compilation? y/n:

type no after the colon.

After the package is installed, load it with:

library(tidyverse)

On Blackboard, in the Resources folder is a file called Lab data. Download the lab data into the GEOG316 folder that you created. Make sure to unzip the folder if need be. In that folder is a csv called HotSpotsData2012.csv that we will read into R.

dat <- read_csv("Datasets/HotSpotsData2012.csv")

A nice feature of read_csv() is that it prints out the column names as well as their datatype. Notice that the file path is in quotes because it is a string. If your script is in the same folder as the subfolder Datasets, this code should read in the data. If it is in a different location on your computer, you will need to adjust the path.

There are three additional arguments that you may need to use with the read_csv() function.

  • Sometimes at the top of a file are a couple of lines of that describe the file. You can use skip = n to skip the first n lines of data, or you can use comment = "#" to drop all lines that start with #.

  • Sometimes there will not be column names in your csv file. In that case you can either specify col_names = FALSE to name your columns sequentially from X1 to Xn, or you can specify col_names with a character vector of your column names.

  • There may be NAs in your dataset. You can tell R which values to convert to NAs with na = "." where . is the value that represents missing data in your datset.

There are other readr functions for different kinds of datasets, including read_tsv(), which reads tab-delimitate files and read_delim, which reads in any kind of delimited file but their is pretty much the same.

Try reading in HotSpotsData2012.txt.

dat.2 <- read_tsv("Datasets/HotSpotsData2012.txt")

Print out both dat and dat2. Are they the same?

Another nice thing about using the readr functions to read in data is that they give us what is called a tibble. A tibble is a data.frame in the tidyverse that behaves nicely, like only printing out the first 10 rows by default and showing you the dimensions. For our purposes, the terms tibble and data.frame can be used interchangeably. If you ever encounter code that won’t work with a tibble, you can change it into a data.frame with as.data.frame().

2 Writing data in R

Writing data is just another way to say saving data. There are many ways to export data in R, but here we will talk about .RData files. .RData is specific to R and can store as many objects as you like in a single file. If your project used a number of different data.frames, you could save them all in a single .RData file.

You can tell R which items you want to save:

a <- data("mtcars")

save(a, dat, dat.2, file = "myobjects.RData") # This saves a, dat, and dat.2

Notice that the file myobjects.RData showed up in your Files panel.

Or, if you have a lot of objects loaded and you want to save them all, you can save your entire workspace.

save.image(file = "projectimage.RData")

Let’s clear all of the objects from our environment. Remember that you can use rm(x) to remove object x. You can also use rm(list = ls()) to remove all the objects in your environment. But be careful! You can’t undo this action. That is part of why we write good code and save often, so we can recreate our analysis.

rm(list = ls())

To load the data, you simply use load().

load("projectimage.RData")

If you need to, you can also save your data.frame to a csv file.

write_csv(dat, "my_data.csv")

3 Generating data

It is often useful to generate random data when working with new functions or packages, plotting data, or testing functions that you created. You did this in the last lab when we looked at histograms. Don’t forget that it is a good practice to set a seed first so that your work is reproducible. You need to set a seed before any random number generation.

R offers several theoretical frequency distributions from which to generate random data. The one that you have already used is the rnorm() function which draws samples from a normal distribution with a mean and standard deviation that you specify. The syntax for this function is rnorm(n, mean = _, sd = _), where the number of samples is given by an integer n that the user specifies. The arguments mean and sd are optional; if they are not specified, then the default theoretical frequency distribution will be a

For example, let’s create a vector of 100 random data points drawn from a normal distribution with a mean of 50 and standard deviation of 10.

set.seed(1234)
rnorm(100, mean = 50, sd = 10)

The r in rnorm() stands for random and is the code R uses for functions that randomly draw a sample from a population of a specified theoretical frequency distribution. The norm in rnorm() stands for normal and specifies the shape of the frequency distribution. Other distributions that can be accessed from the R base package are:

Function Distribution
rexp() Exponential
rgamma() Gamma
rpois() Poisson
rweibull() Weibull
rt() Student t
rchisq Chi square
rlnorm Log normal
runif Uniform

If you want to take a random sample of existing data, you use the sample(x, size) function, where x is the vector (or data.frame column because remember, a data.frame column is a vector) that you want to sample from and size is the number of samples that you want to draw. You can also optionally specifiy whether or not you want Sampling with replacement means that we can have more elements in our sample than were in the vector that we sampled from.

x <- 1:10

set.seed(1234)
sample(x, 5)

sample(x, 5)
sample(x, 5)

set.seed(1234)
sample(x, 5)

set.seed(1234)
sample(x, 20, replace = T)

Notice that if you don’t set a seed, you will get a different sequence each time. In some cases this is desirable but here we want to ensure that everyone gets the same answers.

4 Descriptive statistics

In the last lab, you were introduced to descriptive statistics; in this lab you will use descriptive statistics to examine real world data. Imagine that you wish to determine the effect that various teaching methods have on the ability of students to remember a map. For your expirement you present a choropleth map to people in one of three ways:

  1. Control group—You show the students the entire map all at once.

  2. Sequenced group—You show the students the map in stages.

  3. Effective procedures group—You show the entire map all at once, but you then explain the different parts of the map.

After people have been exposed to the map in these ways, you ask them true-false questions about the map that they saw, and you record whether they answered the question correctly and how quickly they answered it.

In these exercises you will examine the response times using numerical and visual summaries.

5 Exercises

Make sure that you have the file “Reacdata.csv” in your data folder. Open the file with a text editor. Right click on the file in your folder explorer and go to Open with and then TextEdit (Mac) or Notepad (Windows). Examine the structure. (1) Are there headings?

Read in the file and store it in a variable called dat. Notice that both variables were read in as doubles (numbers). We want Group to be a factor because the number represents a category. Add:

col_types = cols(Group = col_factor(),
                 Resptime = col_double())

to your function call. Make sure to add a comma between the function arguements. This will ensure that Group is read in as a factor. Print dat to see that this worked.

Let’s get some descriptive statistics to compare the response times between the three groups. We will use two new functions to do this, group_by() and group_map(). group_by() tells R that you want to perform an operation by groups instead of performing the operation on an entire column.

dat <- group_by(dat, Group)

Print dat again and notice that now the printed information shows you the number of groups.

group_map() tells R what function you want to apply to the groups, in this case, the summary() function.

group_map(dat, summary, digits = 6)
# Specifying digits tells R the maximum number of significant
# figures to print. We want to see some decimal places!

Let’s examine the histograms for the different groups. We are going to use a different plotting function this time, ggplot(). ggplot() makes it easy to create beautiful data visualizations.

First we create a ggplot object and tell it what data to use, and which variables (columns) we want to plot. Telling ggplot what variables to use is called an aesthetic mapping, which is what the aes() does.

ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(Resptime)) +

Then we add components. Here we tell ggplot what type of plot we want.

geom_histogram()

Go ahead and create a histogram of all the response times.

ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(Resptime)) + 
  geom_histogram()

The warning that prints in red is just telling us that the default number of bins (30) might not be appropriate. In fact, we only have 52 observations in our dataset, so 30 bins is probably too many. Let’s try 10.

ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(Resptime)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 10)

Histograms are visual summaries of the data. Summaries by nature are generalizations. Ten bins provides a better generalization of the data.

It is easy to create a histogram for each group so that we can compare them. We just add a component to our ggplot. The mean by, so we want to facet by group.

ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(Resptime)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 10) +
  facet_wrap(~ Group)

Neat, huh? To illustrate how neat, let me show you the code to make a similar plot not using ggplot().

m1 <- subset(dat, Group == 1) 
m2 <- subset(dat, Group == 2) 
m3 <- subset(dat, Group == 3)

op <- par(mfrow = c(1, 3), pty = "s")

x <- m1$Resptime
h <- hist(x, 
          breaks = seq(0,10000,500), 
          xlim = c(0, 10000),
          ylim = c(0, 8))

x <- m2$Resptime
h <- hist(x, 
          breaks = seq(0,10000,500), 
          xlim = c(0, 10000),
          ylim = c(0, 8))

x <- m3$Resptime
h <- hist(x, 
          breaks = seq(0,10000,500), 
          xlim = c(0, 10000),
          ylim = c(0, 8))

Let’s show a theoretical normal curve on top of the histograms for each group. These curves are defined by the mean and standard deviation of each group. Don’t worry about the details, we just want to compare the shapes of the histograms to the normal distributions.

x <- dat %>% 
  filter(Group == 1)

xfit <- seq(0, max(x$Resptime), length = 40)
yfit <- dnorm(xfit, mean = mean(x$Resptime), sd = sd(x$Resptime)) 
yfit <- yfit*diff(h$mids[1:2])*length(x$Resptime) 

fit <- tibble(xfit = xfit, yfit = yfit)

x %>% 
ggplot(aes(Resptime)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 20) +
  geom_line(fit, mapping = aes(xfit, yfit), color = "red") +
  ggtitle("Group 1")
